642–1673","1650–1677":"1650–1677","1616–Male":"1616–Deceased","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1677":"1677","1622":"1622","1720":"1720","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1696":"1696","1651":"1651","1673":"1673","1650":"1650","about 1642":"about 1642","1616":"1616","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jameson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Jamison  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jamerson","meanings":["English: variant of   Jameson  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jimmerson","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: variant of   Jameson  , based on a pet form of the personal name <i>James</i>."]},{"name":"Jamison","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English and Scots <i>Jami(e)son</i>, <i>Jameson</i>, <i>Jem(i)son</i> ‘son of <i>James</i>’ (see   James  ). <i>Jameson</i> and <i>Jamison</i> are mainly found in northern England, especially in Northumberland and Durham, while in Scotland the more usual form is   Jamieson  , but all three versions occur on either side of the border.","Scottish: variant of   McCamish  ."]},{"name":"Jimison","meanings":["English (County Durham): variant of   Jameson  ."]},{"name":"Jimerson","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: variant of   Jameson  , based on a pet form of the personal name."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705212,"age":4,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":26,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705216,"age":72,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705217,"age":104,"year":"1720","julianDay":2349277,"title":"South Sea Bubble","description":"The South Sea Bubble Bill was passed by the House of Lords in 1720. This allowed the South Sea company to monopolize trade with South America. The company underwrote the English National Debt which promised 5% interest from the government. As shares rose exponentially, many companies were created and many fortunes were made. The stocks crashed and many people lost their money which caused them to become destitute overnight and suicide was common.  Robert Walpole took charge of the South Sea Bubble Financial Crisis by dividing the national debt between the Bank of England, the Treasury, and the Sinking Fund.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/South-Sea-Bubble/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - South Sea Bubble","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"John Jameson was born in 1616, in England. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sarah Porter. He died in Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America."},"et":{"1616–":"1616–Surnud","1622–1696":"1622–1696","1642–1673":"1642–1673","1650–1677":"1650–1677","1616–Male":"1616–Surnud","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1677":"1677","1622":"1622","1720":"1720","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1696":"1696","1651":"1651","1673":"1673","1650":"1650","about 1642":"umbes 1642","1616":"1616","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","England":"England"},"fi":{"1616–":"1616–Kuollut","1622–1696":"1622–1696","1642–1673":"1642–1673","1650–1677":"1650–1677","1616–Male":"1616–Kuollut","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1677":"1677","1622":"1622","1720":"1720","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1696":"1696","1651":"1651","1673":"1673","1650":"1650","about 1642":"noin 1642","1616":"1616","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","England":"England"},"fr":{"1616–":"1616–Décédé","1622–1696":"1622–1696","1642–1673":"1642–1673","1650–1677":"1650–1677","1616–Male":"1616–Décédé","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1677":"1677","1622":"1622","1720":"1720","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1696":"1696","1651":"1651","1673":"1673","1650":"1650","about 1642":"environ 1642","1616":"1616","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginie, Amérique coloniale britannique","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"John Jameson est né en 1616, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Sarah Porter. Il est décédé à Henrico, Virginie, Amérique coloniale britannique."},"de":